<p>My publication-fear was deeply rooted in how I chose to display my writing. I have a buried desire to publish my more thoughtful work so I designed with that ideal in mind. The consequence of doing so made me to feel trapped and I, very effectively, throttled my own creativity.</p>

<hr class="--small" />

<h2 id="frames">Frames</h2>

<p>Creating is very fragile. Everything you do and experience affects your output. Conscious or not, weâ€™re always looking at the frame which houses our work.</p>

<figure>
    <img src="/img/posts/052519-insta.jpg" alt="Screenshot of original Instagram app" />
    <figcaption>
        <p>Image credit: <a href="https://designmodo.com/comparing-ios-designs-apps/">DesignModo.com</a></p>
    </figcaption>
</figure>

<p>Take a look at Instagram as an example. The square photo restriction felt like it had a lot to do with the devices at the time. As time went on, users became more <em>aware</em> of the frame and creative output was altered specifically because of the unique crop.</p>

<p>Although more photographic ratios are allowed now, there remains a couple which arenâ€™t, and so weâ€™re still making concessions.</p>

<p>If youâ€™re a photographer who wants prints than weâ€™re talking about cropping an image twice for displayâ€“once for print, once for the â€˜gram. Or maybe you never print. Maybe you just do it for â€˜gram. That feels strange to me.</p>

<h3 id="other-blogs-have-this-issue">Other Blogs Have This Issue</h3>

<figure>
    <img src="/img/posts/052519-rands.jpg" alt="Screenshot of Rands' website" />
    <figcaption>
        <p>Screenshot of <a href="http://randsinrepose.com">RandsInRepose.com</a></p>
    </figcaption>
